{{short description|A hypothesized galaxy with no, or very few, stars}}
A '''dark galaxy''' is a hypothesized [[galaxy]] with no, or very few, stars. They received their name because they have no visible stars,<ref name="definition">{{cite web|url=http://www.zmescience.com/space/dark-galaxy-evidence-spotted-0707201/ |title=First evidence of dark galaxies from the early Universe spotted |publisher=Zmescience.com |date=2012-07-11 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> but may be detectable if they contain significant amounts of gas. Astronomers have long theorized the existence of dark galaxies, but there are no confirmed examples to date.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Alfalfa "Almost Darks" Campaign: Pilot VLA HI Observations of Five High Mass-To-Light Ratio Systems|journal = The Astronomical Journal|date = 2015-02-01|issn = 0004-6256|pages = 72|volume = 149|issue = 2|doi = 10.1088/0004-6256/149/2/72|first = John M.|last = Cannon|first2 = Charlotte P.|last2 = Martinkus|first3 = Lukas|last3 = Leisman|first4 = Martha P.|last4 = Haynes|first5 = Elizabeth A. K.|last5 = Adams|first6 = Riccardo|last6 = Giovanelli|first7 = Gregory|last7 = Hallenbeck|first8 = Steven|last8 = Janowiecki|first9 = Michael|last9 = Jones|arxiv = 1412.3018 |bibcode = 2015AJ....149...72C }}</ref> Dark galaxies are distinct from intergalactic gas clouds caused by [[Galactic tide|galactic tidal interactions]], since these gas clouds do not contain [[dark matter]], so they do not technically qualify as galaxies. Distinguishing between intergalactic gas clouds and galaxies is difficult; most candidate dark galaxies turn out to be tidal gas clouds.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Is GBT 1355+5439 a dark galaxy?|url = http://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/abs/2013/07/aa21965-13/aa21965-13.html|journal = Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume = 555|pages = L7|accessdate = 2015-09-29|doi = 10.1051/0004-6361/201321965|year = 2013|last1 = Oosterloo|first1 = T. A.|last2 = Heald|first2 = G. H.|last3 = De Blok|first3 = W. J. G.}}</ref> The best candidate dark galaxies to date include HI1225+01,<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Arecibo Legacy Fast ALFA Survey|url = http://egg.astro.cornell.edu/alfalfa/HI1225+01.php|website = egg.astro.cornell.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-29}}</ref> AGC229385,<ref>{{Cite journal|title = (Almost) Dark HI Sources in the ALFALFA Survey: The Intriguing Case of HI1232+20|journal = The Astrophysical Journal|date = 2015-03-01|issn = 0004-637X|pages = 96|volume = 801|issue = 2|doi = 10.1088/0004-637X/801/2/96|first = Steven|last = Janowiecki|first2 = Lukas|last2 = Leisman|first3 = Gyula|last3 = Józsa|first4 = John J.|last4 = Salzer|first5 = Martha P.|last5 = Haynes|first6 = Riccardo|last6 = Giovanelli|first7 = Katherine L.|last7 = Rhode|first8 = John M.|last8 = Cannon|first9 = Elizabeth A. K.|last9 = Adams|arxiv = 1502.01296 |bibcode = 2015ApJ...801...96J }}</ref> and numerous gas clouds detected in studies of quasars.

On 25 August 2016, astronomers reported that [[Dragonfly 44]], an [[ultra diffuse galaxy]] (UDG) with the [[mass]] of the [[Milky Way]] [[galaxy]], but with nearly no discernable [[star]]s or galactic structure, may be made almost entirely of [[dark matter]].<ref name="AJL-20160825">{{cite journal |author=Van Dokkum, Pieter et al. |title=A High Stellar Velocity Dispersion and ~100 Globular Clusters For The Ultra-Diffuse Galaxy Dragonfly 44 |date=25 August 2016 |journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal Letters]] |doi=10.3847/2041-8205/828/1/L6 |volume=828 |issue=1 |page=L6|arxiv = 1606.06291 |bibcode = 2016ApJ...828L...6V |url=http://scholarworks.sjsu.edu/physics_astron_pub/174 }}</ref><ref name="NS-20160825">{{cite web |last=Hall |first=Shannon |title=Ghost galaxy is 99.99 per cent dark matter with almost no stars |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2102584-ghost-galaxy-is-99-99-per-cent-dark-matter-with-almost-no-stars/ |date=25 August 2016 |work=[[New Scientist]] |accessdate=27 August 2016 }}</ref><ref name="WP-20160826">{{cite news |last=Feltman |first=Rachael |title=A new class of galaxy has been discovered, one made almost entirely of dark matter |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2016/08/25/a-new-class-of-galaxy-has-been-discovered-one-made-almost-entirely-of-dark-matter |date=26 August 2016 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>

==Observational evidence==
Large surveys with sensitive, but low resolution radio telescopes like [[Arecibo Observatory|Arecibo]] or the [[Parkes Observatory|Parkes Telescope]] look for [[Hydrogen line|21&nbsp;cm emission]] from atomic hydrogen in galaxies. These surveys are then matched to optical surveys to identify any objects with no optical counterpart, i.e. sources with no stars. 

Another way astronomers search for dark galaxies is to look for hydrogen absorption lines in the spectra of background [[quasar]]s. This technique has revealed many intergalactic clouds of hydrogen, but following up candidate dark galaxies is difficult, since these sources tend to be too far away, and are often optically drowned out by the bright light from the quasar.

==Nature of dark galaxy==

===Origin===
In 2005, astronomers found gas cloud [[VIRGOHI21]] and attempted to determine what it was and why it caused such a gravitational pull on galaxy [[NGC 4254]]. After years of running out of other explanations, some have concluded that VIRGOHI21 is a dark galaxy, due to the massive effect it had on NGC 4254.<ref name="universetoday">{{cite web|author=Fraser Cain |url=http://www.universetoday.com/1888/no-stars-shine-in-this-dark-galaxy/ |title=No Stars Shine in This Dark Galaxy |publisher=Universetoday.com |date=2007-06-14 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>

===Size===
The actual size of dark galaxies is unknown because they cannot be observed with normal telescopes. There have been various estimations, ranging from double the size of the Milky Way<ref name="spacedaily">{{cite web|url=http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Arecibo_Survey_Produces_Dark_Galaxy_Candidate.html |title=Arecibo Survey Produces Dark Galaxy Candidate |publisher=Spacedaily.com |date=2006-04-07 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> to the size of a small [[#HE0450-2958|quasar]].

===Structure===
Dark galaxies are composed of [[dark matter]]. Furthermore, dark galaxies are theoretically composed of hydrogen and [[cosmic dust|dust]].<ref name="universetoday" />  Some scientists support the idea that dark galaxies may contain stars.<ref name="newscientist">{{cite web |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn12100-dark-galaxy-continues-to-puzzle-astronomers.html |title=Dark galaxy' continues to puzzle astronomers |accessdate=2008-02-26 |publisher=[[New Scientist]]|author=[[Stuart Clark (author)|Stuart Clark]]}}</ref> Yet the exact composition of dark galaxies is unknown because there is no conclusive way to spot them so far. However, astronomers estimate that the mass of the gas in these galaxies is approximately 1 billion times that of the Sun.<ref name="FirstDirectDetection">{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2012/10/121030161234.htm |title=First Direct Detection Sheds Light On Dark Galaxies |publisher=Zmescience.com |accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref>

===Methodology to observe dark bodies===
Dark galaxies contain no visible stars, and are not visible using optical telescopes. The Arecibo Galaxy Environment Survey (AGES) is a current study using the [[Arecibo radio telescope]] to search for dark galaxies, which are predicted to contain detectable amounts of [[Hydrogen line#Uses in radio astronomy|neutral hydrogen]]. The Arecibo radio telescope is useful where others are not because of its ability to detect the emission from this neutral hydrogen, specifically the 21&nbsp;cm line.<ref>{{cite web|author=in Astronomy |url=http://www.dailygalaxy.com/my_weblog/2009/12/darkmatter-galaxy-ten-billion-xs-the-mass-of-the-sun.html |title=Invisible Dark-Matter Galaxy has Ten Billion Xs the Mass of the Sun |publisher=Dailygalaxy.com |date=2009-12-23 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>

===Alternative theories===
Scientists do not have much explanation for some astronomic events, so some use the idea of a dark galaxy to explain these events. Little is known about dark galaxies, and some scientists believe a dark galaxy is actually a newly forming galaxy. One such candidate is in the Virgo cluster. This candidate contains very few stars. Scientists classify this galaxy as a [[Galaxy formation and evolution|newly forming galaxy]], rather than a dark galaxy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsblaze.com/story/20091130170354drex.nb/topstory.html |title=Drexler's Dark Matter Prediction Confirmation Followed His New Book |publisher=Newsblaze.com |date=2009-11-30 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>
Scientists say that the galaxies we see today only began to create stars after dark galaxies. Based on numerous scientific assertions, dark galaxies played a big role in many of the galaxies astronomers and scientists see today. Martin Haehnel, from Kavli Institute for Cosmology at the University of Cambridge, claims that the precursor to the Milky Way galaxy was actually a much smaller bright galaxy that had merged with dark galaxies nearby to form the Milky Way we currently see. Multiple scientists agree that dark galaxies are building blocks of modern galaxies. Sebastian Cantalupo of the University of California, Santa Cruz, agrees with this theory. He goes on to say, "In our current theory of galaxy formation, we believe that big galaxies form from the merger of smaller galaxies. Dark galaxies bring to big galaxies a lot of gas, which then accelerates star formation in the bigger galaxies." Scientists have specific techniques they use to locate these dark galaxies. These techniques have the capability of teaching us more about other special events that occur in the universe; for instance, the “cosmic web”. This “web” is made of invisible filaments of gas and dark matter believed to permeate the universe, as well as “feeding and building galaxies and galaxy clusters where the filaments intersect.”<ref name="FirstDirectDetection"/>

==Potential dark galaxies==

===HE0450-2958===
{{main|HE0450-2958}}

HE0450-2958 is a [[quasar]] at [[redshift]] z=0.285. [[Hubble Space Telescope]] images showed that the quasar is located at the edge of a large cloud of gas, but no host galaxy was detected for the quasar. The authors of the Hubble study suggested that one possible scenario was that the quasar is located in a dark galaxy.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Magain P. | display-authors = etal | year = 2005 | title = Discovery of a bright quasar without a massive host galaxy | bibcode = 2005Natur.437..381M | journal = Nature | volume = 437 | issue = 7057| pages = 381–4 | doi=10.1038/nature04013|arxiv = astro-ph/0509433 | pmid=16163349}}</ref>  However, subsequent analysis by other groups found no evidence that the host galaxy is anomalously dark, and demonstrated that a normal host galaxy is probably present,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Merritt | first = David | display-authors = etal | authorlink=David Merritt | year = 2006 | title = The nature of the HE0450-2958 system | bibcode = 2006MNRAS.367.1746M | journal = [[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]]| volume = 367 | issue = 4| pages = 1746–1750 | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2006.10093.x|arxiv = astro-ph/0511315 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kim |first1=Minjin |last2=Ho |first2=Luis |last3=Peng |first3=Chien |last4=Im |first4=Myungshin |title=The Host Galaxy of the Quasar HE 0450-2958 |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |date=2007 |volume=658 |issue=1 |pages=107–113 |doi=10.1086/510846 |bibcode=2007ApJ...658..107K|arxiv=astro-ph/0611411 }}</ref>, so the observations do not support the dark galaxy interpretation.

===HVC 127-41-330===
{{main|HVC 127-41-330}}
HVC 127-41-330 is a cloud rotating at high speed between [[Andromeda Galaxy|Andromeda]] and the [[Triangulum Galaxy]]. Astronomer Josh Simon considers this cloud to be a dark galaxy because of the speed of its rotation and its predicted mass.<ref name="simon">{{cite journal |author = Josh Simon | title =  Dark Matter in Dwarf Galaxies: Observational Tests of the Cold Dark Matter Paradigm on Small Scales | year = 2005  | url = http://www.astro.caltech.edu/~jsimon/thesis/jdsthesis.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060913084945/http://www.astro.caltech.edu/~jsimon/thesis/jdsthesis.pdf|archivedate=2006-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last =Battersby | first =Stephen | title =Astronomers find first 'dark galaxy' | work =New Scientist | url = https://www.newscientist.com/article.ns?id=dn4272 | date =2003-10-20 |accessdate=December 22, 2012}}</ref>

===Smith's Cloud===
{{main|Smith's Cloud}}
Smith's Cloud is a candidate to be a dark galaxy, due to its projected mass and survival of encounters with the Milky Way.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= New Scientist |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20427354.200-dark-galaxy-crashing-into-the-milky-way.html |title= Dark galaxy crashing into the Milky Way |date= 22 November 2009 |number= 2735 |accessdate= 2009-12-12 }}</ref>

===VIRGOHI21===
{{main|VIRGOHI21}}

Initially discovered in 2000, VIRGOHI21 was announced in February 2005 as a good candidate to be a true dark galaxy.<ref name=newscientist/><ref name="firstDark">{{cite news| last =Clark | first =Stuart  | title =Astronomers claim first 'dark galaxy' find | work =NewScientist.com news service | url =https://www.newscientist.com/article.ns?id=dn7056 | date=2005-02-23| accessdate =2006-10-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| last =Shiga | first =David | title =Ghostly Galaxy: Massive, dark cloud intrigues scientists | journal =Science News Online | volume =167 | issue =9 | pages =131 | date =2005-02-26 | url =http://www.sciencenews.org/view/generic/id/5929/title/Ghostly_Galaxy_Massive%2C_dark_cloud_intrigues_scientists | accessdate =2008-09-14 | doi =10.2307/4015891| jstor =4015891}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| last =Britt | first =Roy | title =First Invisible Galaxy Discovered in Cosmology Breakthrough | work =Space.com | url = http://www.space.com/scienceastronomy/050223_dark_galaxy.html | date =2005-02-23 }}</ref> It was detected in 21-cm surveys, and was suspected to be a possible cosmic partner to the galaxy [[NGC 4254]]. This unusual-looking galaxy appears to be one partner in a cosmic collision, and appeared to show dynamics consistent with a dark galaxy (and apparently inconsistent with the predictions of the [[Modified Newtonian dynamics|Modified Newtonian Dynamics (MOND)]] theory).<ref>{{cite journal| last =Funkhouser| first =Scott| title =Testing MOND with VirgoHI21 | journal =Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society | volume =364| issue =1| page =237 | year =2005 | arxiv = astro-ph/0503104 | doi =10.1111/j.1365-2966.2005.09565.x | bibcode=2005MNRAS.364..237F}}</ref>  However, further observations revealed that VIRGOHI21 was an intergalactic gas cloud, stripped from NGC4254 by a high speed collision.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Optically Unseen H I Detections toward the Virgo Cluster Detected in the Arecibo Legacy Fast ALFA Survey|journal = The Astrophysical Journal Letters|date = 2007-08-01|issn = 0004-637X|pages = L15–L18|volume = 665|issue = 1|doi = 10.1086/521100|first = Brian R.|last = Kent|first2 = Riccardo|last2 = Giovanelli|first3 = Martha P.|last3 = Haynes|first4 = Amélie|last4 = Saintonge|first5 = Sabrina|last5 = Stierwalt|first6 = Thomas|last6 = Balonek|first7 = Noah|last7 = Brosch|first8 = Barbara|last8 = Catinella|first9 = Rebecca A.|last9 = Koopmann|bibcode = 2007ApJ...665L..15K }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Tidal Debris from High-Velocity Collisions as Fake Dark Galaxies: A Numerical Model of VIRGOHI 21|journal = The Astrophysical Journal|date = 2008-02-01|issn = 0004-637X|pages = 787–797|volume = 673|issue = 2|doi = 10.1086/524868|first = Pierre-Alain|last = Duc|first2 = Frederic|last2 = Bournaud|arxiv = 0710.3867 |bibcode = 2008ApJ...673..787D }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Haynes, Martha P. |author2=Giovanelli, Riccardo |author3=Kent, Brian R. | title= NGC 4254: An Act of Harassment Uncovered by the Arecibo Legacy Fast ALFA Survey | journal=[[Astrophysical Journal]] | year=2007 | volume=665 | issue=1 | pages=L19–22 | doi=10.1086/521188 | bibcode=2007ApJ...665L..19H|arxiv = 0707.0113 }}</ref>  The high speed interaction was caused by infall into the [[Virgo cluster]].

