{{Infobox power station | name = Tarfaya Wind Farm | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = Tarfaya Wind Farm | image_alt = | location_map = Morocco | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|27|57|24|N|12|0|0|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = [[Morocco]] | location = [[Tarfaya]] | status = Operational | construction_began = January 2013 | commissioned = 2014 | decommissioned = | cost = >[[United States Dollar|US$]]560 million | owner = | operator = [[Nareva]] | ps_units_operational = 131 | ps_units_manu_model = | wind_hub_height = | wind_rotor_diameter = | wind_rated_speed = | wind_farm_type = Onshore | wind_site_elevation = | wind_site_usage = | wind_offshore_depth = | wind_offshore_distance = | ps_electrical_capacity = 301 MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = | extra = }} '''Tarfaya Wind Farm''' is a [[wind farm]] in [[Morocco]], located in 20&nbsp;km from [[Tarfaya]].<ref>[http://www.one.org.ma/FR/pages/interne.asp?esp=2&id1=5&id2=54&id3=44&t2=1&t3=1 Projet de parc éolien de Tarfaya]</ref> It was developed by Tarec (Trarfaya Energy Company), a 50/50 joint venture of Nareva Holding and International Power Ltd. Tarfaya Wind Farm is owned and operated by a 50:50 joint venture between the GDF SUEZ and Nareva Holding and it is the Africa's largest capacity wind farms with 131 [[wind turbines]], each generating 2.5 [[Megawatts]] of power, and a total installed capacity of 301 MW.<ref>[http://www.utilities-me.com/article-3227-gdf-suez-launches-560mn-morrocan-wind-farm/ GDF SUEZ launches $560mn Morrocan wind farm]</ref> It was on the list of ten “Most Outstanding African Projects in 2015”, a ranking by [[Jeune Afrique]] magazine. The park was commissioned in December 2014 after two years of work and investment of 5 billion dirhams. Its constructor and operator is Tarec, which sells the power generated to the National Electricity Office. <ref>{{cite news |date= February 7, 2013 |titl