[[File:Y8n6mcch7s601.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Artur Korneyev, Deputy Director of Shelter Object, viewing the ‘elephants foot’ lava flow, Chernobyl NPP. Photographer: Artur Korneyev. Fall 1996.]] '''The Elephant’s Foot''' is an extremely radioactive mass of [[corium (nuclear reactor)|corium]] formed during the [[Chernobyl disaster]] in April 1986, and was discovered in December 1986. It is named for its wrinkly appearance, resembling the foot of an [[elephant]]. The corium mass is beneath Reactor N. 4 of the [[Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant]], in under-reactor room 217.<ref name=Record>{{cite book |title= Chernobyl Record: The Definitive History of the Chernobyl Catastrophe |author= R. F. Mould |publisher= CRC Press |year= 2000 |isbn= 9781420034622 |page= 130}}</ref>
The Elephant's Foot is a large mass of black corium with many layers, externally resembling tree bark and glass. The mass is quite dense, unyielding to a drill but able to be damaged by a [[Kalashnikov rifle]]. By June 1998, the outer layers of the mass began to turn to dust and the entire mass was starting to crack. The mass has penetrated through at least {{convert|2|m|abbr=on}} of concrete.<ref name=Record/>
The radiation level near the mass was approximately 8,000 [[Roentgen (unit)|roentgen]]s per hour, an invariably lethal dosage of radiation.<ref>{{cite magazine |title= Daily Report: Soviet Union |issue= 235-239 |editor= United States Foreign Broadcast Information Service |publisher= The Service |year= 1989}}</ref>
==Composition==
It is composed chiefly of [[silicon dioxide]], with traces of [[uranium]].<ref name=Role>{{cite book |title= Role of GIS in Lifting the Cloud Off Chernobyl |volume= 10 |series= NATO Science: Earth and environmental sciences |editor= Jaromir Kolejka |edition= illustrated |publisher= Springer Science & Business Media |year= 2002 |isbn= 9781402007682 |page= 72}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title= Decade of Disaster |author= Ann Larabee |edition= illustrated |publisher= University of Illinois Press |year= 2000 |isbn= 9780252068201 |page= 50}}</ref> The mass is largely homogeneous, though the [[Depolymerization|depolymerized]] silicate glass contains occasional crystalline grains of [[zircon]]. These grains of zircon are not elongated, suggesting a moderate crystallization rate. While [[uranium dioxide]] [[Dendrite (crystal)|dendrites]] grew quickly at high temperatures within the lava, the zircon began crystallization during slow cooling of the lava. Despite the distribution of uranium bearing particles not being uniform, the radioactivity of the mass is evenly distributed.<ref>{{cite journal |title= Radioactivity distribution in fuel-containing materials (Chernobyl “lava”) and aerosols from the Chernobyl “Shelter” |last1= Vlasova |first1= Irina |last2= Shiryaev |first2= Andrey |last3= Ogorodnikov |first3= Boris |last4= Burakov |first4= Boris |last5= Dolgopolova |first5= Ekaterina |last6= Senin |first6= Roman |last7= Averin |first7= Alexey |last8= Zubavichus |first8= Yan |last9= Kalmykov |first9= Stepan |journal= Radiation Measurements |volume= 83 |pages= 20-25 |year= 2015 |publisher= Elsevier |doi= |url= https://doi.org/10.1016/j.radmeas.2015.06.005}}</ref>
